
<refentry id="multitap">
<indexterm id="IndexMultitap"><primary>multitap</primary></indexterm>
  <refentryinfo><title>Signal Modifiers:Delay</title></refentryinfo>
  <refmeta>
    <refentrytitle>multitap</refentrytitle>
  </refmeta>

  <refnamediv>
    <refname>multitap</refname>
    <refpurpose>
      Multitap delay line implementation.
    </refpurpose>
  </refnamediv>
 
  <refsect1>
    <title>Description</title>
    <para>
      Multitap delay line implementation.
    </para>
  </refsect1>
 
  <refsect1>
    <title>Syntax</title>
    <synopsis>ares <command>multitap</command> asig [, itime1, igain1] [, itime2, igain2] [...]</synopsis>
  </refsect1>
 
  <refsect1>
    <title>Initialization</title>
    <para>
      The arguments <emphasis>itime</emphasis> and <emphasis>igain</emphasis> set the position and gain of each tap.
    </para>

    <para>
      The delay line is fed by <emphasis>asig</emphasis>.
    </para>
  </refsect1>

  <refsect1>
    <title>Examples</title>
    <para>
      Here is an example of the multitap opcode. It uses the file <ulink url="examples/multitap.csd"><citetitle>multitap.csd</citetitle></ulink>
      <example>
        <title>Example of the multitap opcode.</title>
        <xi:include href="examples-xml/multitap.csd.xml" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"/>
      </example>
     This results in two delays, one with length of 1.2 and gain of .5, and one with length of 1.4 and gain of .2.
    </para>
  </refsect1>
  
